I have talked to some professors, I'll talk to some more of course, but I'm writing this paper next semester. This is just prep work.

Since chemistry theory is about reactants colliding to create a product, this can be neatly modeled as PDEs. Glycolosys has about 100 chemicals throughout all of its stages and the rate of change of the final product is a function of the rate of change of all of the reactants going down 100 or so steps all the way to the initial inputs. I'm using a system of 100 PDEs to model glycolysis. Now the thing is, no one knows --all-- of these constants so I will write an algorithm that solve this system with random constants, and does that a bunch of times with different constants. Then I will compare all the solutions and see if the constants that are common knowledge match up, and eliminate the ones that don't. Then I'll see if the surviving solutions would represent something that would kill the cell. Then I eliminate those.

Then I would have ways that glycolysis could work. And that would be the end goal. It's purely theoretical, but if scientists perform such an analysis on all chemical reactions in the body, and perform a meta-analysis on all of these models we could have a mathematical way to describe all the ways human biochemistry would work and not kill the human. That would of course be a big deal.
